fields.physical_description:
Walnut veneer on oak. Cresting of carved and silvered pine. The upper stages enclosed by tow doors with arched tops enclosing fielded panels veneered with burr-walnut with cross-banded corners and moulded edges. The top with moulded and shaped cornice is surmounted by a shaped cresting pierced and carved with S-scrolls and flowers. The interior is divided vertically into three compartments each with sliding shelves and a drawer at the bottom. At the base of the upper stage a shallow central drawer with a candle slide on each side. On the inside of the left hand door is pasted a printed almanac for the year 1712.

Bureau with falling front supported on lopers. The front veneered with burr-walnut with cross-banded borders, interior with well covered by sliding panels. On each side atier of three drawers, and in the centre two long drawers, each with a shaped front surmounted by three pairs of pigeonholes. Each pair can be pulled out to reveal a secret drawer behind. Lower stage containing two long and two short drawers with cross-banded borders. Moulded base with restored bun feet. The brass fittings old but not original to the piece. The locks and both keys original.
fields.marks: A printed London almanac, dated 1712 has been pasted to the inside of the left hand door. The almanac has been stamped with a small red stamp that may say penny? There is also an inscription in pencil along the bottom of the almanac;  requires assistance of paper conservation to read with a UV light.
fields.credit: Gift of Brigadier W. E. Clark CMG, DSO through The Art Fund
fields.history_note: John Hardy notes in the green cat.: 'June '67 - Brigadier Clark told us he went to Cheshire to buy this cabinet with a dealer from York named Greenfield ?. JH '68'.
